In[1]:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Define A and B
A = np.array([[2, 3], [-4, 1]])
B = np.array([6, -8])

# Solve using inverse
A_inv = np.linalg.inv(A)
solution = np.dot(A_inv, B)
x, y = solution

print(f"The solution is x = {x}, y = {y}")

The solution is x = 2.142857142857143, y = 0.5714285714285714

x_vals = np.linspace(-10, 10, 100)

# Rearranged line equations:
y1 = (6 - 2 * x_vals) / 3     # from 2x + 3y = 6
y2 = (-8 + 4 * x_vals)        # from -4x + y = -8

# Plotting
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))                               #8 inches wide and 6 inches tall.
plt.plot(x_vals, y1, label="2x + 3y = 6", color="blue")
plt.plot(x_vals, y2, label="-4x + y = -8", color="red")
plt.scatter(x, y, color="black", label=f"Solution: ({x:.2f}, {y:.2f})", zorder=5)  #black point (dot) at the intersection of the two lines.

plt.axhline(0, color='black', linewidth=0.5)
plt.axvline(0, color='black', linewidth=0.5)
plt.grid(color='gray', linestyle='--', linewidth=0.5)
plt.xlabel("x-axis")
plt.ylabel("y-axis")
plt.title("Intersection of Two Lines")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Unique Solution :When all three planes intersect at a single point, as shown in the example above.

iii. Extend this concept to next dimensions take any 3 plane equations and find their intersection points. Investigate the cases when there are (a) No solution, many solutions and (c) unique solution.

Extend 3D

In[4]:
"""(a) No Solution
If planes are parallel or inconsistent, like:
x+y+z=1,
x+y+z=2,
x+y+z=3,
Here, all three planes have the same normal vector but different constants, meaning they are parallel and distinct, 
hence they do not intersect at any point.

When the system of equations represents inconsistent planes (e.g., all planes are parallel or overlap partially without a common point),
there is no solution.

 No common point  No solution.

(b) Infinite Solutions
If all planes intersect along a common line or are coincident.

All three equations represent the same plane, so there are infinitely many solutions (any point on the plane satisfies all three equations).

Conclusion: Multiple intersection points  Infinite solutions


(c) Unique Solution
When all three planes intersect at a single point, as shown in the example above."""
Out[4]:
'(a) No Solution\nIf planes are parallel or inconsistent, like:\nx+y+z=1,\nx+y+z=2,\nx+y+z=3,\n\n No common point  No solution.\n\n(b) Infinite Solutions\nIf all planes intersect along a common line or are coincident.\n\n(c) Unique Solution\nWhen all three planes intersect at a single point, as shown in the example above.'

(a) No Solution

In[15]:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D
from matplotlib.patches import Patch

# Define coefficients: all planes have same normal vector => parallel
coeffs = np.array([[1, 1, 1],   # Plane 1: x + y + z = 1
                   [1, 1, 1],   # Plane 2: x + y + z = 2
                   [1, 1, 1]])  # Plane 3: x + y + z = 3

# Different constants (parallel and distinct planes)
consts = [1, 2, 3]

# Generate meshgrid for plotting
x_vals = np.linspace(-5, 5, 20)
y_vals = np.linspace(-5, 5, 20)
X, Y = np.meshgrid(x_vals, y_vals)

# Set up 3D plot
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')    #fig.add_subplot(111)  adds 1 row, 1 column, 1st subplot (a single plot).

                                             #projection='3d'  makes it a 3D plot, allowing you to plot surfaces or points in 3D space.

# Colors for each plane
colors = ['red', 'green', 'blue']

# Plot each plane
for i in range(3):
    a, b, c = coeffs[i]
    d = consts[i]
    Z = (d - a * X - b * Y) / c  # Solve for z
    ax.plot_surface(X, Y, Z, alpha=0.5, color=colors[i])

# Axis labels
ax.set_xlabel('X-axis')
ax.set_ylabel('Y-axis')
ax.set_zlabel('Z-axis')
ax.set_title("Case (a): No Solution - Parallel Planes")

# Custom legend (since plot_surface doesn't support label)
legend_elements = [Patch(facecolor=colors[i], label=f'Plane {i+1}: x+y+z={consts[i]}') for i in range(3)]
ax.legend(handles=legend_elements)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

(b): Infinite Solutions

In[6]:
# Case (b): Infinite Solutions - All planes are the same (coincident)
A2 = np.array([[1, 1, 1],
               [2, 2, 2],
               [3, 3, 3]])

B2 = np.array([5, 10, 15])  # All are multiples => same plane

rank_A2 = np.linalg.matrix_rank(A2)
rank_A2_aug = np.linalg.matrix_rank(np.column_stack((A2, B2)))

if rank_A2 == rank_A2_aug and rank_A2 < A2.shape[1]:
    print("Case (b) - Infinite solutions: The system is dependent (planes are coincident or intersect along a line).")
else:
    print("Case (b) - Unexpected result.")

Case (b) - Infinite solutions: The system is dependent (planes are coincident or intersect along a line).

# Create the figure and 3D axis
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')

# Create a grid of x and y values
xx, yy = np.meshgrid(range(-10, 10), range(-10, 10))

# Define z from the plane: x + y + z = 5  z = 5 - x - y
z_plane = 5 - xx - yy

# Plot the coincident planes (same surface with different colors/transparencies)
ax.plot_surface(xx, yy, z_plane, alpha=0.6, color='blue', label='Plane 1')   # transparency leve;
ax.plot_surface(xx, yy, z_plane, alpha=0.3, color='green', label='Plane 2')
ax.plot_surface(xx, yy, z_plane, alpha=0.3, color='red', label='Plane 3')

# Annotate one point on the plane
ax.scatter(1, 1, 3, color='black', s=50, label="Point on plane")

# Labels and legend
ax.set_xlabel('X-axis')
ax.set_ylabel('Y-axis')
ax.set_zlabel('Z-axis')
ax.set_title("Case (b): Infinite Solutions (Coincident Planes)")
ax.legend()

plt.show()

from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')

xx, yy = np.meshgrid(range(-10, 10), range(-10, 10))

z1 = 6 - xx - yy
z2 = (14 - 2 * xx + yy) / 3
z3 = 2 - 4 * xx - 3 * yy

ax.plot_surface(xx, yy, z1, alpha=0.5, color='red', label='Plane 1')
ax.plot_surface(xx, yy, z2, alpha=0.5, color='blue', label='Plane 2')
ax.plot_surface(xx, yy, z3, alpha=0.5, color='green', label='Plane 3')

ax.scatter(x, y, z, color='black', s=100, label=f"Intersection Point ({x:.2f}, {y:.2f}, {z:.2f})")

ax.set_xlabel('X-axis')
ax.set_ylabel('Y-axis')
ax.set_zlabel('Z-axis')
ax.set_title('Intersection of Three Planes')
ax.legend()

plt.show()

Task 2: Effect of Outliers on Mean vs Median

PART A: UNIFORM DISTRIBUTION

Step A.1: Generate 10,000 points from 2D Uniform Distribution

Outliers are data points that are very different from most other values in a dataset.

Mean:The mean is the average of a set of numbers.

Median:The median is the middle number in a sorted list.

In[9]:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Seed for reproducibility
np.random.seed(42)    #code uses it to make sure the "random" results are repeatable and consistent every time you run it.

# Generate 10,000 points in 2D uniformly in the range [0, 1]
x_uniform = np.random.uniform(0, 1, 10000)
y_uniform = np.random.uniform(0, 1, 10000)

# Calculate mean and median
mean_x = np.mean(x_uniform)
median_x = np.median(x_uniform)

mean_y = np.mean(y_uniform) 
median_y = np.median(y_uniform)

print(f"Uniform Distribution (Without Outliers):")
print(f"Mean (x, y) = ({mean_x:.4f}, {mean_y:.4f})")
print(f"Median (x, y) = ({median_x:.4f}, {median_y:.4f})")

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
plt.scatter(x_uniform, y_uniform, alpha=0.3, label='Uniform Points')
plt.title("Uniform Distribution (without Outliers 
plt.xlabel("x")
plt.ylabel("y")
plt.grid(True)
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Uniform Distribution (Without Outliers):
Mean (x, y) = (0.4942, 0.5045)
Median (x, y) = (0.4925, 0.5059)

Step A.2: Add Outliers & Recalculate Mean/Median

In[10]:
# Add 5 extreme outliers far outside the [0, 1] range
x_outliers = np.array([10, 12, 15, -8, -5])
y_outliers = np.array([-10, -12, 14, 9, 11])

# Combine original and outliers
x_combined = np.concatenate([x_uniform, x_outliers])
y_combined = np.concatenate([y_uniform, y_outliers])

# New mean and median
mean_x_out = np.mean(x_combined)
median_x_out = np.median(x_combined)

mean_y_out = np.mean(y_combined)
median_y_out = np.median(y_combined)

print(f"\nUniform Distribution (With Outliers):")
print(f"Mean (x, y) = ({mean_x_out:.4f}, {mean_y_out:.4f})")
print(f"Median (x, y) = ({median_x_out:.4f}, {median_y_out:.4f})")

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
plt.scatter(x_combined, y_combined, alpha=0.3, label='With Outliers')
plt.scatter(x_outliers, y_outliers, color='red', label='Outliers', s=100, marker='x')
plt.title("Uniform Distribution (with Outliers)")
plt.xlabel("x")
plt.ylabel("y")
plt.grid(True)
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Uniform Distribution (With Outliers):
Mean (x, y) = (0.4963, 0.5055)
Median (x, y) = (0.4925, 0.5059)

# Generate 10,000 points from a 2D normal distribution (mean=0, std=1)
x_gaussian = np.random.normal(0, 1, 10000)
y_gaussian = np.random.normal(0, 1, 10000)

# Mean and Median
print(f"\nGaussian Distribution (Without Outliers):")
print(f"Mean (x, y) = ({np.mean(x_gaussian):.4f}, {np.mean(y_gaussian):.4f})")
print(f"Median (x, y) = ({np.median(x_gaussian):.4f}, {np.median(y_gaussian):.4f})")

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
plt.scatter(x_gaussian, y_gaussian, alpha=0.3, label='Gaussian Points')
plt.title("Gaussian Distribution (without Outliers)")
plt.xlabel("x")
plt.ylabel("y")
plt.grid(True)
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Gaussian Distribution (Without Outliers):
Mean (x, y) = (0.0033, -0.0155)
Median (x, y) = (0.0054, -0.0124)
